<subSubSection id="A6F16558BF2E2A453AE9FD6AFC53FC89" pageId="3" pageNumber="436" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="EE5436D3BF2E2A453AE9FD6AFC53FC89" blockId="3.[151,1436,151,1005]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">
<emphasis id="DC9FEAC1BF2E2A453AE9FD6AFED3FD6C" bold="true" box="[199,334,727,752]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">Etymology.</emphasis>
The present name is derived from the Latin “ 
<emphasis id="DC9FEAC1BF2E2A4539AAFD6AFC23FD6C" bold="true" box="[900,958,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">brevi</emphasis>
”(short) and “ 
<emphasis id="DC9FEAC1BF2E2A453E4AFD65FB32FD6C" bold="true" box="[1124,1199,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">spinus</emphasis>
”(spine), it refers to theshort spines on reduced inner distal processes on original gonocoxites.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A6F16558BF2E2A453AE9FCA2FBF7FC54" pageId="3" pageNumber="436" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="EE5436D3BF2E2A453AE9FCA2FBF7FC54" blockId="3.[151,1436,151,1005]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">
<emphasis id="DC9FEAC1BF2E2A453AE9FCA2FEA9FCA4" bold="true" box="[199,308,799,824]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">Remarks</emphasis>
: This new species clearly belongs to the 
<taxonomicName id="29EB4D50BF2E2A4538D5FC9DFCE3FCA4" box="[763,894,800,824]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Ptecticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longipennis">
<emphasis id="DC9FEAC1BF2E2A4538D5FC9DFCE3FCA4" box="[763,894,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">longipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group by the following shared characters: apical 
<number id="582324F4BF2E2A453AB9FCF9FF3CFCC0" box="[151,161,836,860]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number id="582324F4BF2E2A453A85FCF9FF26FCC0" box="[171,187,836,860]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436" value="4.0">4</number>
of wings darkened, and a fusion of the epandrium and paraprocts. It is very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="29EB4D50BF2E2A453ED9FCF8FE80FC1C" authority="Wiedemann" authorityName="Wiedemann" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Ptecticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longipennis">
<emphasis id="DC9FEAC1BF2E2A453ED9FCF8FA01FCC0" box="[1271,1436,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">P. longipennis</emphasis>
Wiedemann
</taxonomicName>
by external morphological characters, but it can be distinguished by the wholly yellow pleura; the male terminalia, are very close to 
<taxonomicName id="29EB4D50BF2E2A453839FC30FC01FC38" authority="Rozkosny &amp; Kovac" authorityName="Rozkosny &amp; Kovac" box="[535,924,908,933]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Ptecticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longispinus">
<emphasis id="DC9FEAC1BF2E2A453839FC30FD29FC38" box="[535,692,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">P. longispinus</emphasis>
Rozkošný &amp; Kovac
</taxonomicName>
, but the inner distal processes of gonocoxites are considerably reduced and their inner spine-like projections are only minute (Fig, 
<number id="582324F4BF2E2A453E62FC12FBC1FC54" box="[1100,1116,943,968]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436" value="5.0">5</number>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
